Users see a 'Cancelled' error message when quickly switching tabs. Find and fix the bug:

```swift
@Observable @MainActor final class SearchViewModel {
    var state: ViewState<[Result]> = .idle

    func search(query: String) async {
        state = .loading
        do {
            let results = try await searchService.search(query: query)
            state = .loaded(results)
        } catch {
            state = .error(error.localizedDescription)  // Shows "cancelled"
        }
    }
}
```

evals.expected_output:
When the user switches tabs, SwiftUI cancels the .task running search() — this throws CancellationError, which is caught by the generic catch block and exposed as an error state showing 'Cancelled' to the user. Fix: catch CancellationError separately before the generic catch and return without changing state:

```swift
} catch is CancellationError {
    return  // Task cancelled — silent exit, state unchanged
} catch {
    state = .error(error.localizedDescription)
}
```

Rule: CancellationError must always be handled silently, never surfaced to users.

