evals.expected_output:
Missing memory leak detection. Add `addTeardownBlock { [weak sut] in XCTAssertNil(sut) }` in setUp immediately after creating sut — this verifies sut is actually deallocated when set to nil in tearDown, catching any retain cycles.

For the load() test — since the test class and ViewModel share @MainActor, no XCTestExpectation is needed. Simply await and assert directly:

```swift
func testLoadSetsLoadedState() async throws {
    await sut.load()
    if case .loaded(let products) = sut.state {
        XCTAssertEqual(products.count, 1)
    } else {
        XCTFail("Expected .loaded, got \(sut.state)")
    }
}
```

Use `await fulfillment(of:)` only when asynchronous callbacks are involved — not needed here since load() is directly awaited.

